- Please share so we can get as many of our kids as possible to attend!

post_text:
LUMBERJACKS!!!

Hello everyone!

Since doing school at home was a new experience for many of us, I thought it might be fun to make a video of what we are thankful for during this pandemic. Maybe it's that you get to spend more time with your family or you are thankful that through online school, you have become more responsible. When you have decided what you are thankful for, please wear something that signifies you are a Council Lumberjack and have someone take a video of you saying what you are thankful for during this pandemic and why. You could take the video in front of a woodpile or something else that would give your video a Lumberjack feel. Mrs. Cook is helping me with this project and has organized that for each person who sends a video in, a tree will be planted. Please email your video to me, ieppich@csd13.org by June 12th. Have a great summer!

Thanks,

Isabelle Eppich

post_text:
Attention Fall Sports Athletes:

CHS is working to return to normal. The first step is getting our summer sports going! We will be following health and safety precautions to limit the spread of COVD-19. Additionally, parents must sign a waiver allowing their student back on school grounds. Please contact the school for the form!

Football: Weight training begins Monday, June 1st 6-8 pm. Make sure to bring cleats for a workout on the field. Sign up for SportsYOU using the attached code for your summer events calendar.

Cheer: There will be a meeting Friday, June 5th at 4:00 pm at the high school for any high school students interested in joining cheer. We’ll bring cookies!

post_text: Please plan on joining us to shine a light tonight!
shared_text:
Council High School
April 7 at 2:31 PM ·

Lumberjack Family:

To show support for our students, families, spring athletes and coaches, and especially our 2020 seniors, Council High School will turn on the lights on the football field as a beacon to show that we are thinking of our students and families in this difficult time. We have hope that we will soon be back together stronger and better than ever.

We will hit the lights this Friday at 8:20 pm (20:20) for twenty minutes. This event will be drive by only! Please stay in your cars, but join us for a cruise by the field, share a honk or two, and show off that Lumberjack pride!

#BeTheLightID

post_text: Over 100 masks were made this past week by CHS students, teachers and volunteers. The masks have been distributed to local nursing homes, health care workers, Council EMS, St. Alphonsus and St. Lukes clinics/hospitals and local elderly citizens. This is a great example of FCS (Family & Consumer Science) skills put into action. #Lumberjackstrong!

post_text:
To support the students of our local community CTC is providing wifi hotspots for students to be able to get their work done if they don’t have the bandwidth or internet at their home.

The two hotspots are located at the Council CTC office across from the Senior Center, and at the Council Library.

These locations have a WiFi SSID of Free Student WiFi and require no password. They have increased the bandwidth at the library to handle student needs of uploading and downloading assignments.

While you are in these areas please follow the rules of social distancing.

On behalf of Council School District we want to thank Cambridge Telephone Company for making this possible.

post_text: Teachers worked through Spring Break to prepare online lessons for our junior high and high school students! Monday morning is the first day ‘back to class.’ Please help us encourage students to log in and keep up with their school work! If you do not have internet or computer access available for your student, please call the school for help getting that set up. Paper copies of assignments will be made available in the meantime. Thank you for helping us keep education going for our students! Time to hit the books!

We will have the following:
Several kinds of tomatoes
Strawberries, Blueberries, Raspberries, Oregano, Basil, Parsley, Lavender, Asparagus, Kale, Spinach, Lettuce, Cabbage, Cauliflower, Broccoli, Celery, Pumpkin, Zucchini, Squash, Cucumber, Bell Peppers, Jalapeno, Habanero Peppers. Several kinds of flowers in hanging baskets as well as in flats.

post_text: All Idaho school superintendents just finished a conference call with Governor Little, SDE, and State Health officials. They will NOT be issuing a statewide school closure and encourage all of us to keep our students in school saying that health officials see no science based value to short term school closures. So we are business as usual this week at Council School District.

A message from our ASB President:

Hello Lumberjack Fans‼️

This week is Tip-Off week (basically homecoming but for basketball) for CHS. Come join us Tuesday and Thursday as we take on big competitors in our league! The games Tuesday are against Cascade and start at 6 with girls varsity, then boys varsity at 7:30. Cascade is a TOUGH team and our players could use a BIG crowd cheering! These games will be a BLACK out, so please come to the game wearing BLACK! ⚫️ The games against Horseshoe Bend on Thursday will be Lumberjack Spirit games, so please come wearing red, white, and black.

Please feel free to share this and spread the word. Go Jacks!❤️🤍🖤

post_text: Our cross-country team represented CHS at the Dash and Splash meet on Saturday, August 24th. Both athletes did extremely well. Levi crushed his goal for the year of 24 minutes by a little over a minute; his time for the race was 22:54, and he came in the top 1/2 of all the athletes running. Miles's time was 20:07, and he was in the top 1/3. There were approximately 100+ athletes running from many different schools (McCall, Caldwell, New Plymouth, Mountain Home, Cole Valley Christian to name a few). Coach Stanford says that she is so proud of these boys because they have been training hard these past two weeks. Their next meet is this Thursday in New Plymouth at 6 pm.

U.S. Forest Service - Payette National Forest
May 5, 2019 at 6:00 AM ·

Recently, Council High School teachers organized an Earth/Arbor Day celebration.

Students planted a pollinator garden, cleaned up highway litter, bagged and gave away wood chip as mulch for local gardens, worked at the local community garden, and pruned the school orchard.

Local Forest Service employees attended and helped students with these tasks, taking the opportunity to work side-by-side with a great bunch of local youth and educators.

post_text: Attn High School Parents: On Friday, April 26th Council High School will be celebrating Arbor Day! This is our make-up day for missing several snow days. Only grades 9-12 are required to attend. School will begin at the usual time with an assembly. Students will break into groups to plant trees, work in gardens, clean up campus, or landscape. Every student will receive a t-shirt and have the opportunity to tie-dye it! We will have a BBQ lunch and a nice day in the sun! For more information, call the school at (208) 253-4217
